9","1550–Male":"1550–Deceased","1571–1630":"1571–1630","1580–Female":"1580–Deceased","1520–1622":"1520–1622","1525–1609":"1525–1609","30 January 1571":"30 January 1571","1550":"1550","1571":"1571","1570":"1570","1580":"1580","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1525":"1525","1546":"1546","1600":"1600","1622":"1622","1589":"1589","1587":"1587","1520":"1520","1630":"1630","23 September 1589":"23 September 1589","1585":"1585","1609":"1609",",, England":"England, United Kingdom","Iwerne Courtney, Dorset, England":"Iwerne Courtney, Dorset, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Wormleighton, Warwickshire, England":"Wormleighton, Warwickshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mathon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: from a pet form of the personal name   Mathieu   (see   Matthew  ). Compare   Matton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathieu","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Normand, Andre, Lucien, Pierre, Yvon, Armand, Rosaire, Alphonse, Dominique, Emile, Fernand.","French and Walloon: from the French personal name <i>Mathieu</i>, vernacular derivative of Latin <i>Mathias</i> or <i>Matthaeus</i> (see   Matthew  ). Compare   Matthieu  ."]}]},{"name":"Frances","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Feminine form of   Francis .  In the 16th century the two spellings were used indiscriminately for both sexes, the distinction in spelling not being established until the 17th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705202,"age":8,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705205,"age":19,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705206,"age":21,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705207,"age":35,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705208,"age":37,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705210,"age":50,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Frances Mathon was born in 1550, in Suffolk, England, her father, John Adam Mathon, was 30 and her mother, Iris Candye, was 2